{"title_page": "Cliff Daringer", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name       = Cliff Daringer\n| image      =\n| position   = [[Infielder]]\n| birth_date  = April 10, 1885\n| birth_place = [[Hayden, Indiana]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1971|12|26|1885|4|10}}\n| death_place = [[Sacramento, California]]\n| bats       = Left\n| throws     = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate  = April 20\n| debutyear  = 1914\n| debutteam  = Kansas City Packers\n|finalleague = MLB\n| finaldate  = September 29\n| finalyear  = 1914\n| finalteam  = Kansas City Packers\n|statleague = MLB\n| stat1label = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value = .263\n| stat2label = [[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n| stat2value = 42\n| stat3label = [[Stolen base]]s\n| stat3value = 9\n| teams      =\n* [[Kansas City Packers]] (1914)\n}}\n'''Clifford Clarence Daringer''' (April 10, 1885 \u2013 December 26, 1971) was a Major League Baseball infielder who played for one season. He played in 64 games for the Kansas City Packers during their 1914 season. He was the older brother of [[Rolla Daringer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=daring001cli|title=Cliff Daringer Minor & Independent Leagues Statistics & History|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nBorn on April 10, 1885, Daringer was one of ten children born to Lorenzo Dow Daringer (1844-1892) and Margaret Ann Carr (1847-1940). His father served in the [[6th Indiana Infantry Regiment|6th Indiana Infantry]] during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] and was wounded three times during battle. He died due to complications from these injuries.<ref>{{Find a Grave}}</ref>\n\nDaringer made his Major League debut on April 20, 1914 vs. the [[Newark Peppers|Indianapolis Hoosiers]], getting two hits in two at-bats, as well as his first Major League RBI against [[George Kaiserling]]. After a sub-par season in which he received only 186 plate appearances, Daringer was released by the Packers.\n\nDaringer was also in the starting lineup against the Chicago Whales in the first game in Weegham Park, now known as [[Wrigley Field]]. He went 0-3.\n\nHe married Alice Freeney in 1914 and moved to Sacramento, California in 1917, where he lived until his death on December 26, 1971.\n\nPart of a notorious baseball family, his brother, Howard, was an outfielder for many years in the [[Illinois-Indiana-Iowa League]], while another brother, [[Rolla Daringer|Rolla]], was a two-year Major League shortstop for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. He also had a fourth cousin, [[Paul Derringer]], who won 223 games over a 15-year career with the Cardinals, [[Cincinnati Reds]], and [[Chicago Cubs]] from 1931 to 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thenattydugout.com/daringer-family-history-told-baseball/|title=The Daringer Family: a History Told Through Baseball|last=League|first=Scott Bline in American|last2=Profiles|first2=Historical|date=2014-08-25|website=The Natty Dugout|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10|last3=League|first3=National}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|br=d/darincl01|brm=daring001cli}}\n*{{findagrave}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daringer, Cliff}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball infielders]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Packers players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Hayden, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Lynchburg Shoemakers players]]\n[[Category:Springfield Babes (baseball) players]]\n[[Category:Mt. Clemens Bathers players]]\n[[Category:Saginaw Wa-was players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Veterans players]]\n[[Category:Sacramento Sacts players]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Bronchos players]]\n[[Category:Fort Worth Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Covington Blue Sox players]]\n[[Category:Dubuque Dubs players]]\n[[Category:Freeport Commons players]]\n\n\n{{US-baseball-infielder-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name       = Cliff Daringer\n| image      =\n| position   = [[Infielder]]\n| birth_date  = April 10, 1885\n| birth_place = [[Hayden, Indiana]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1971|12|26|1885|4|10}}\n| death_place = [[Sacramento, California]]\n| bats       = Left\n| throws     = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate  = April 20\n| debutyear  = 1914\n| debutteam  = Kansas City Packers\n|finalleague = MLB\n| finaldate  = September 29\n| finalyear  = 1914\n| finalteam  = Kansas City Packers\n|statleague = MLB\n| stat1label = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value = .263\n| stat2label = [[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n| stat2value = 42\n| stat3label = [[Stolen base]]s\n| stat3value = 9\n| teams      =\n* [[Kansas City Packers]] (1914)\n}}\n'''Clifford Clarence Daringer''' (April 10, 1885 \u2013 December 26, 1971) was a Major League Baseball infielder who played for one season. He played in 64 games for the Kansas City Packers during their 1914 season. He was the older brother of [[Rolla Daringer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=daring001cli|title=Cliff Daringer Minor & Independent Leagues Statistics & History|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nBorn on April 10, 1885, Daringer was one of ten children born to Lorenzo Dow Daringer (1844-1892) and Margaret Ann Carr (1847-1940). His father served in the [[6th Indiana Infantry Regiment|6th Indiana Infantry]] during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] and was wounded three times during battle. He died due to complications from these injuries.<ref>{{https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/45261413/lorenzo-dow-daringer}}</ref>\n\nDaringer made his Major League debut on April 20, 1914 vs. the [[Newark Peppers|Indianapolis Hoosiers]], getting two hits in two at-bats, as well as his first Major League RBI against [[George Kaiserling]]. After a sub-par season in which he received only 186 plate appearances, Daringer was released by the Packers.\n\nDaringer was also in the starting lineup against the Chicago Whales in the first game in Weegham Park, now known as [[Wrigley Field]]. He went 0-3.\n\nHe married Alice Freeney in 1914 and moved to Sacramento, California in 1917, where he lived until his death on December 26, 1971.\n\nPart of a notorious baseball family, his brother, Howard, was an outfielder for many years in the [[Illinois-Indiana-Iowa League]], while another brother, [[Rolla Daringer|Rolla]], was a two-year Major League shortstop for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. He also had a fourth cousin, [[Paul Derringer]], who won 223 games over a 15-year career with the Cardinals, [[Cincinnati Reds]], and [[Chicago Cubs]] from 1931 to 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thenattydugout.com/daringer-family-history-told-baseball/|title=The Daringer Family: a History Told Through Baseball|last=League|first=Scott Bline in American|last2=Profiles|first2=Historical|date=2014-08-25|website=The Natty Dugout|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10|last3=League|first3=National}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|br=d/darincl01|brm=daring001cli}}\n*{{findagrave}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daringer, Cliff}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball infielders]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Packers players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Hayden, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Lynchburg Shoemakers players]]\n[[Category:Springfield Babes (baseball) players]]\n[[Category:Mt. Clemens Bathers players]]\n[[Category:Saginaw Wa-was players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Veterans players]]\n[[Category:Sacramento Sacts players]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Bronchos players]]\n[[Category:Fort Worth Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Covington Blue Sox players]]\n[[Category:Dubuque Dubs players]]\n[[Category:Freeport Commons players]]\n\